{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VCbRKaNQjkuJ8G6qLbi1bN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Elasticsearch is running on plain HTTP (not HTTPS) internally. The task is to:\n1. Make it accessible at https://es.example.com (HTTPS to the ingress, which will proxy to HTTP internally)\n2. Block plain HTTP access\n\nI need to:\n1. Create a self-signed TLS certificate for es.example.com\n2. Create a TLS Secret in the elasticsearch namespace\n3. Create an Ingress resource with:\n   - `kubernetes.io/ingress.class: nginx` or `ingressClassName: nginx`\n   - TLS section referencing the secret\n   - `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/force-ssl-redirect: \"true\"` to redirect HTTP requests to HTTPS\n\nI'm debating whether \"HTTP access should not succeed\" means redirecting to HTTPS or completely blocking HTTP. The standard approach with nginx ingress is to use `force-ssl-redirect`, which sends a 308 redirect—technically the HTTP request doesn't serve content directly. I could also use a configuration snippet to return a 403 for HTTP, but the redirect approach is more conventional. I should also check if Elasticsearch needs authentication configured.\n\nNow I'll generate a self-signed certificate for es.example.com using the openssl-toolbox pod that's already available in the cluster.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":759,"cache_read_input_tokens":29879,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":759},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0f5e2a71-6447-4c17-a166-d2160649ae08","uuid":"dcf9881a-f2c6-4946-9156-af6c9f449dda","request_id":"req_011CcQBoLP4W7WrhRrFaTUrd"}
